  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_3199937483" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3199937483" />
    <a title="Jamie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/68583290-jamie"><img alt="Jamie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1542573579p2/68583290.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3199937483?book_show_action=true">Feb 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jamie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jamie" href="/user/show/68583290-jamie">Jamie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/68583290-jamie?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/68583290-jamie?shelf=history-ancient">history-ancient</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3199937483" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14451084795168334446">In this book H.W.F. Saggs does an excellent job explaining key milestones on the road to civilization. For example, why did it get its start in Mesopotamia? What combination of essential factors made that the place where the fire was lit? The answer appears to be climate, water, and population growth. Southern Mesopotamia does not get enough rain to sustain farming, and so was dependent on water from the rivers, but at some point the amount of naturally irrigated land could no longer support all</span>
  <span id="freeText14451084795168334446" style="display:none">In this book H.W.F. Saggs does an excellent job explaining key milestones on the road to civilization. For example, why did it get its start in Mesopotamia? What combination of essential factors made that the place where the fire was lit? The answer appears to be climate, water, and population growth. Southern Mesopotamia does not get enough rain to sustain farming, and so was dependent on water from the rivers, but at some point the amount of naturally irrigated land could no longer support all its people. In other places war or migration would have reduced the headcount, but here<br /><br /><blockquote>We may reasonably assume that pressure for change did develop during the Ubaid period: the value of communal effort in irrigation was evident to all, and as command of irrigation technology advanced, larger-scale works could be attempted, but these would require populations larger than a single village. If several villages combined into a larger social structure for such a purpose, other economic and political advantages would appear, such as increased opportunities for specialization, and greater bargaining power with other groups; and the advantages inherent in growth in community size would become evident, generating pressure towards development of cities.” (p. 33)</blockquote><br /><br />That is a logical, straightforward answer. Behind it were generations of scholars carefully sifting the historical evidence and combining the findings of multiple disciplines to arrive at the most likely scenario. The process continues today, of course, and is always subject to further revision. Saggs provides the most likely explanations for a number of advances, organized by topic rather than chronologically or by individual civilizations. The book has chapters on monumental construction, writing, education, city life, trade, law, international relations, mathematics and astronomy, and religion. From them the reader gains an appreciation of the hard won advances that ultimately led to the creation of the modern world.<br /><br />The chapter on monumental construction shows that the most important factor in building the pyramids was not labor but organization. The workers seem to have been primarily free rather than slaves, some of whom worked year-round, such as the stone cutters. Most of them, up to 100,000 at a time, were seasonally employed, working only about three months a year in accordance with the flooding of the Nile and the sowing and harvesting of crops. Saggs does some quick math based on the number of workers and estimates of the amount of time it took to place the massive stone blocks and concludes that many of the pyramids could have been completed in about six years. <br /><br />Mesopotamia also built monuments on a grand scale, though never to the same height and breadth as Egypt, and since they did not have ready access to large quantities of stone they used mud brick. The great structures required constant upkeep because over time the occasional rainstorms allowed water to penetrate inside and begin eroding them, and ancient travelers commented on seeing leaning ziggurats, towers, and city walls. Eventually these had to be abandoned and all we see today are stunted remnants.<br /><br />Saggs does a fine job explaining the creation and spread of writing from pictographs to abstract representations of words, syllables, and individual sounds. He also provides a clear explanation of how they were deciphered thousands of years later, giving credit to the brilliant scholars across Europe who were responsible. Like the Rosetta Stone, most of the breakthroughs relied on finds of works written in multiple languages, which could be used to painstakingly translate the symbols of a known language into those of the unknown one. Also, since language is more than vocabulary, it further required working out all the other grammatical elements, such as declensions and tense forms. This was especially impressive in the case of Sumerian, the Ur-language of the earliest cuneiform, since it was an isolate, with no known related tongues to help give hints. Cuneiform was used for about three thousand years, and adapted for use with dozens of languages, yet today scholars can read most of them, to the point where the translations Saggs provides in this book are as clear and easy to follow as translations of modern languages.<br /><br />The early civilizations developed highly sophisticated systems for dealing with their increasingly complex societies. Bodies of written laws allowed judges to give consistent interpretations in legal cases, facilitating the creation of trade networks which stretched thousands of miles. Lapis lazuli, for instance, was widely prized but its only known source was deep in what is now Afghanistan; and yet it shows up as far away as Egypt and even Crete. Foreign traders were not to be interfered with, and if they were robbed or murdered and those guilty could not be found, the closest town was required to make good the losses. Kings sent diplomats to other countries, and communicated frequently with one other (often in Akkadian, the lingua-franca of international relations much like French would be until recently in Europe, even though it was not a language spoken in most countries). They arranged for their sons and daughters to marry to help seal alliances, and sent gifts to one another to maintain cordial relations.<br /><br />The study of medicine started with brilliant observations and considerable progress, and then ossified into sacred dogma, preventing further advances. As a result, medicine in the ancient world was a blend of effective practical techniques, such as for setting bones and using beneficial herbs, overlaid with a huge amount of hokum in the form of spells, charms, and divination. Later, in Europe, a similar situation would result when the writings of Galen and Hippocrates became so enshrined that actual observations were discarded if they disagreed with the masters. <br /><br />The author does a good job explaining the surprisingly complex mathematical techniques in use, including a fascinating multi-page tutorial on ancient multiplication and division in systems that had no zero to act as placeholder, and instead used a complicated but ingenious system of factoring numbers to arrive at the correct answer. I was so impressed by it that I read the section twice and then created some sample problems to solve on my own.<br /><br />Astronomy was important to the rising civilizations to synchronize their crop cycles. Their observations allowed them to track the length of the year to a high degree of precision, and from an early age to predict eclipses. Saggs also makes an interesting point about how the ancient calendars still exert influence in the present day.<br /><br /><blockquote>A purely lunar calendar may be adequate for peoples who are still in a nomadic agricultural stage, and almost all primitive peoples began with a lunar calendar, which is sometimes tenaciously retained even when changing conditions make it no longer appropriate: Muslims still use such a calendar unmodified, whilst Judaism retains lunar months in its otherwise solar year. Christianity uses, alongside the solar calendar by which Christmas is fixed, an old lunar calendar for calculating the date of Easter and the linked festivals from Septuagesima to Trinity. This lunar element in the three great monotheistic religions reflects the nomadic background of their earliest source, Israelite religion. (p. 229)</blockquote><br /><br />The book ends with a discussion of religion. The polytheistic beliefs of the ancient world make sense when they are seen as outgrowths of the earliest human attempts to understand the numinous. Initially the gods seem to have been abstractions; the spirit of the river was simply the river, with no anthropomorphic traits. Later they became personified and in an interesting theological twist, the earlier abstractions were recast as evils which the new hero gods had to defeat in order to prepare the world of humans. An echo of this can be seen in ancient Greece, where Saturn and the Titans were defeated by Zeus and the younger gods to usher in the age of man. Pantheons began to form, and while most cities and kings had their patron deities, once human sacrifice had been eliminated the polytheistic religions were far more tolerant and congenial than the later monotheisms, with their multiple One True Faiths, and all the misery that has resulted from them.<br /><br /><i>Civilization Before Greece and Rome</i> is well written, with an engaging, non-academic style. My only concern about it is that it was published in 1989, which is long enough ago that there are probably more modern interpretations of some things in this book. As a general introduction to ancient civilizations, however, it is a good starting point which helps frame the environments which allowed Greece and Rome to rise and flourish.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14451084795168334446" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


